The head is similar in width to the trunk and separated from it by an indistinctly narrower neck (
Fig. 7
). The trunk slightly and gradually widens to its widest point located about its middle (U 57 ). The trunk then gradually narrows up to a narrow, weakly marked furca base on U 87 . Furcal branches are close to each other. The furcal indentation is parabolic, and the ends of adhesive tubes point outwards. Adhesive tubes are straight, long and thin and do not taper towards their ends. The ends of the adhesive tubes are blunt.

Scales on the body vary slightly in size (see
Table 3
). They slightly and gradually become smaller from the dorsal side, through the dorsolateral, lateral, ventrolateral and ventral sides, to the ciliary bands. Furthermore, the scales become larger from the beginning of the head to the widest point of the trunk. Scales in the last longitudinal rows adjoining the ciliary bands are aligned diagonally at an angle of around 20 ° towards the bands.

subSection.paragraph:
The Baltic Sea is the largest brackish water system in the world. In many respects the Baltic resembles an estuary and is exceptional with areas where freshwater, brackish water and marine species coexist (
Feistel et al. 2008
). This is why the Gastrotricha fauna in the brackish waters of the Baltic Sea is unique, however it is relatively poor in species diversity compared to typically marine habitats, e.g. the Mediterranean Sea or the North Sea ( e.g.
Balsamo et al. 1997
; Todaro et al. 2003 ;
Gerlach 2004
;
Schmidt-Rhaesa et Todaro 2006
). There are few typically brackish taxa. To date, only four species belonging to Chaetonotida that live in this specific type of habitats have been observed, with
Heterolepidoderma sinus
spec. nov.
being the potential fifth taxon (
Balsamo et al. 2014
;
Kolicka et al. 2014
). Brackish water species can be found in the benthal and the interstitial water of bays, lagoons and the mouths of rivers (Grilli et al. 2010 ;
Balsamo et al. 2014
).
Kisielewski ( 1990 )
suggests that the small number of brackish water species is related to lower attractiveness of brackish habitats for gastrotrichs ( e.g. due to salinity fluctuations), rather than the fact that these habitats have not been investigated as much as other habitats. Low species diversity in the brackish Baltic Sea is also noted in case to other group of microinvertebrates e.g . tardigrades (
Zawierucha et al. 2015
). Brackish habitats can contain species considered typically marine as well as typically freshwater. All Gastrotricha found to date on the Polish coast should be considered as species that may inhabit brackish waters, viz. they are euryhaline (see
Kolicka et al. 2014
). For example, the traditionally marine taxon
Turbanella
Schultze, 1853
contains several species that often inhabit a variety of different saline environments:
T. hyalina
Schultze, 1853
,
T. cornuta
Remane, 1925
and
T. lutheri
Remane, 1952
, all of which have been found in various localities of brackish water in the Baltic Sea and in seas with high salinity ( e.g.
Rudescu 1967
;
Kisielewski 1975
; Kieneke et al. 2012 ;
Kånneby 2014 a
, b ;
Kolicka et al. 2014
).
T. lutheri
has also been observed in freshwater in beach seeps in Roscoff ( France ) (
Kisielewski 1987 b
).
Kånneby and Wicksten ( 2014 )
point out that widespread species, i.e., those found in extremely different environments, can either be regarded as taxa with very high tolerance or as complexes of cryptic species adapted only to a narrow range of specific factors.

Gastrotricha are considered to have originated in the sea (
Kieneke et al. 2008
). However, our understanding of how they adapted from marine to freshwater ecosystems is still incomplete (Todaro et al. 2012 ;
Kånneby et al.

2013 ). The role brackish habitats play in primary and secondary colonisation of the freshwater realm by Gastrotricha is not fully understood (
Kisielewski 1990
;
Kånneby et al. 2013
;
Kånneby et Wicksten 2014
). This is why it is important to thoroughly investigate the taxa that inhabit these special ecosystems. Further research on brackish ecosystems, including the Puck Bay, may bring a better understanding of how Gastrotricha could have colonised adjacent habitats.
